The National Human Rights Commission has called on governments at all levels to increase youth inclusiveness in governance, decision making and peace resolutions. The Executive Secretary of the Commission, Tony Ojukwu, yesterday, in a press statement commemorating this year’s International Youth Day (IYD) has also called on governments to strengthen institutions and programmes that will enable the effective implementation of the United Nations  Security  Council Resolution 2250 on Youth, Peace and Security. Ojukwu who said that the action will not only reduce youth restlessness in the country, but will also create an enabling approach to ensuring the participation of youths in decision making in peace and security. While lamenting that the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic  on  young  people  has  been enormous   and even   leading to  the denial  of their fundamental human rights as enshrined under the Nigerian Constitution and other regional and international human rights instruments, he said the   theme   of   this  year’s  commemoration which is: “Youth Engagement for Global Action” was  appropriate for inspiring young people to play leading roles in community and national development.